for &quot;some&quot; sequence of elements that generate (which space might have smaller dimension than , or in case the ring is not a field it might not be a free module at all).

=== A bogus &quot;proof&quot;: ===
One persistent elementary but &quot;incorrect&quot; argument for the theorem is to &quot;simply&quot; take the definition
formula_134
and substitute for , obtaining
formula_135

There are many ways to see why this argument is wrong. First, in the Cayley–Hamilton theorem, is an &quot; matrix&quot;. However, the right hand side of the above equation is the value of a determinant, which is a &quot;scalar&quot;. So they cannot be equated unless (i.e. is just a scalar). Second, in the expression formula_136, the variable λ actually occurs at the diagonal entries of the matrix formula_137. To illustrate, consider the characteristic polynomial in the previous example again:

formula_138

If one substitutes the entire matrix for in those positions, one obtains

formula_139

in which the &quot;matrix&quot; expression is simply not a valid one. Note, however, that if scalar multiples of identity matrices
