then the determinant is indeed zero, but the expanded matrix in question does not evaluate to formula_141; nor can its determinant (a scalar) be compared to &quot;p&quot;(&quot;A&quot;) (a matrix). So the argument that formula_142 still does not apply.

Actually, if such an argument holds, it should also hold when other multilinear forms instead of determinant is used. For instance, if we consider the permanent function and define formula_143, then by the same argument, we should be able to &quot;prove&quot; that . But this statement is demonstrably wrong: in the 2-dimensional case, for instance, the permanent of a matrix is given by

